        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0486.jpg" n="part4_p012.jpg" xml:id="img_0012" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part4_p012.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_12_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>181-
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>Fermany-the teaching elementstrongly—bu t the research element predominantly.
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>Now this gives you already a difference, a very fypical difference, connected
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>with the whole situation in these counties. Therefore the influence of the universites on
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>the cultural life of Germany was only indirect, but very little direct in terms of education.
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>It was great on the English upper class, and it was fundamental on the French bureaucracy.
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>Now let us look at these three function in their historical setting, and their relationship
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>to the problem of religion. First the teaching function of the university. From earlier times,
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>two different congress were at the university, namely the humanities and the professions.
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>In the Middle Age's they were the artes liberales, the liberal arts—today called 'the humanities,'
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_12_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>in this country, through which everybody had to go, in which one learned physics, astronomy,
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>logic, mathematics, and, in which it was necessary, duitoric (which to a great extent means
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>philology), which gave the humanistic pre-condition for the other faculties. Then the other
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>faculties were: the first one, the "queen," as it was called in the Middle Auges: theology.
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>Then the law faculty, and then the medical faculty. These three were the professional faculties.
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>Here we have, from the very beginning, a lot of problem, even besides the religious problem
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>(to which I come instantly), namely the question of the relationship of the professional to the
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>humanities teaching. Has the university—this was the problem—a function which is connected
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>with the practice even in the humanities, even besides the professionaltaining? Here we had
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_12_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>a lot of difficulties with the humanities side of teaching. This side could be understood as mere
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>tout de
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>que je prends bien ces
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>le précaire lʼautreur beaucoup dʼune manié avec vérité
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>ne pas que
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>Vous avez
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_8" n="N008"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_9" n="N009"/>de votre beau
               <lb facs="#facs_12_tr_3_tl_10" n="N010"/>sont
            </p>
            
